Real-world Data Wrangling¶

Introduction:¶

This project endeavors to compile a dataset tailored for Natural Language Processing (NLP) tasks, specifically targeting the named entity disambiguation problem. It aims to gather a diverse array of named entities categorized as persons, locations, and organizations, supplemented with both context and definition. Definitions are sourced from Wikidata, while contextual information is extracted from Wikipedia. Only entities endowed with both context and description are included in the dataset, ensuring relevance and richness for downstream NLP tasks.

1. Gather data¶

In this section, you will extract data using there different data gathering methods and combine the data. the first gathering model is manaul, the second is programmatically using sparql query, and finaly, using Python library.

1.1. Problem Statement¶

This project aims to collect a dataset for NLP tasks, such as named entity disambiguation problem. We have a group of named entities categorized as persons, locations, and organizations. For each named entity, we seek to collect both a context and a definition. Definitions will be sourced from Wikidata, and context will be gathered from Wikipedia. Entities that have both context and description will be labeled with a value of 1.

Dataset 1¶

Type: Excel file with multiple sheets.

I selected this dataset because it offers a varied collection of named entities, encompassing individuals, organizations, and geographic locations. Its inclusivity ensures relevance across a spectrum of Natural Language Processing (NLP) tasks. Moreover, its interchangeability with other datasets containing named entities underscores the flexibility of our methodology, facilitating seamless adaptation to diverse research objectives and domains within NLP.

Methodology: The dataset was gathered manually from different web resources for named entities of types (person, location, and organization). These named entities are from the Palestinian community.

Dataset variables:

Variable Name Description
Name_en1 Name of the person (e.g., 'Hafez Hamdan')
Name_en Name of the organization (e.g., 'Birzeit org')
Lname_en1 Name of the location (e.g., 'Jerusalem', 'New York')

Dataset 2¶

Type: Excel File

Methodology: The dataset was gathered from Wikidata using a SPARQL query to collect information for named entities from dataset 1 that exist in the Wikidata knowledge graph.

I seletected Wikidata as a source of data, as it already conatins the needed information as a knowledge graph for named entities and the nodes are connected with many knowledge bases suh as Wikipedia.

Dataset variables:

Column Name Description
item.type Type of the Wikidata item.
item Item ID of the Wikidata entity.
itemLabel.xml:lang XML language of the item label.
itemLabel.type Type of the item label.
itemLabel Label of the Wikidata entity in the specified language.
itemDescription.xml:lang XML language of the item description.
itemDescription.type Type of the item description.
itemDescription Description of the Wikidata entity in the specified language.
entity_type.type Type of the entity.
entity_type Type of the Wikidata entity.
main_category Main category associated with the item, if available.
altLabel_list.type Type of the alternative label list.
altLabel_list Comma-separated list of alternative labels for the item, if available.
article.type Type of the Wikipedia article.
article URL of the Wikipedia article associated with the item.
wikipediaLabel.xml:lang XML language of the Wikipedia label.
wikipediaLabel.type Type of the Wikipedia label.
wikipediaLabel Label of the Wikipedia article in the specified language.
entity_type_list.type Type of the entity type list.
entity_type_list Comma-separated list of entity types associated with the item.

Dataset 3¶

Type: Excel File.

Methodology: The dataset was gathered from Wikipedia using the Wikipedia library in Python to collect Wikipedia descriptions (one sentence for each named entity), based on the data from Dataset 2. The following sections provide detailed steps for the data gathering techni

I opted for Wikipedia as a data source due to its seamless integration with Wikidata through interconnected nodes. This linkage streamlines the process of extracting contextual information for each named entity, as Wikipedia articles serve as supplementary sources of detailed context. Leveraging Wikipedia in conjunction with Wikidata enables us to gather comprehensive information for each named entity efficiently and effectively, enhancing the richness and relevance of our dataset. ue.

Dataset variables:

Column Name Description
item Item ID of the Wikidata entity.
itemLabel Label of the Wikidata entity.
itemDescription Description of the Wikidata entity.
entity_type Type of the Wikidata entity.
main_category Main category associated with the item, if available.
altLabel_list Comma-separated list of alternative labels for the item.
article URL of the Wikipedia article associated with the item.
wikipediaLabel Label of the Wikipedia article associated with the item.
entity_type_list Comma-separated list of entity types associated with the item.
FirstTwoSentences First two sentences of the Wikipedia description.

1.1.0 SPARQL ENDPOINT¶

1.1.1 Create query function¶

The function below takes a SPARQL query string, queries a sparql service, and returns the result as a pandas DataFrame (a table). Try it on Wikidata Query service

In [4]:
def query_wikidata(sparql_query, sparql_service_url):
    print(sparql_query)
    """
    Query the endpoint with the given query string and return the results as a pandas Dataframe.
    """
    # create the connection to the endpoint
    # Wikidata enforces now a strict User-Agent policy, we need to specify the agent
    # See here https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Wikidata:Project_chat/Archive/2019/07#problems_with_query_API
    # https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/User-Agent_policy
    sparql = SPARQLWrapper(sparql_service_url, agent="Sparql Wrapper on Jupyter example")

    sparql.setQuery(sparql_query)
    sparql.setReturnFormat(JSON)

    # ask for the result
    result = sparql.query().convert()
    return json_normalize(result["results"]["bindings"])

1.1.2 Run our SPARQL query¶

In [5]:
def search_wikidata_label_en(label, lang='en'):
    """
    Searches for entities in Wikidata that match a given label in a specified language.

    This function constructs and sends a SPARQL query to the Wikidata Query Service to find entities
    matching the provided label. The query retrieves various details about the entities including
    their descriptions, types, alternative labels, main categories, and corresponding Wikipedia articles.

    Args:
        label (str): The label to search for in Wikidata.
        lang (str): The language code for the search and the returned labels (default is 'en' for English).

    Returns:
        pandas.DataFrame: A DataFrame containing the search results with columns for article URL, 
                          item ID, item label, item description, entity types, main category, 
                          Wikipedia label, and alternative labels.

    Example:
        >>> search_wikidata_label_en("Albert Einstein")
        # Returns a DataFrame with information about entities related to "Albert Einstein"
    """
    sparql_query = (
        'SELECT DISTINCT ?article ?item ?itemLabel ?itemDescription '
        '(GROUP_CONCAT(DISTINCT(?entity_type); separator = ", ") AS ?entity_type_list) '
        '?main_category ?wikipediaLabel '
        '(GROUP_CONCAT(DISTINCT(?altLabel); separator = ", ") AS ?altLabel_list) WHERE {'
        'SERVICE wikibase:mwapi {'
        'bd:serviceParam wikibase:api "EntitySearch". '
        'bd:serviceParam wikibase:endpoint "www.wikidata.org".'
        f'bd:serviceParam mwapi:search "{label}".'
        f'bd:serviceParam mwapi:language "{lang}" .'
        '?item wikibase:apiOutputItem mwapi:item .'
        '?num wikibase:apiOrdinal true .}'
        '?item wdt:P31 ?entity_type .'
        'MINUS { ?item wdt:P31 wd:Q4167410}'
        'OPTIONAL { ?item wdt:P910 ?main_category}'
        'OPTIONAL { ?item skos:altLabel ?altLabel .}'
        'OPTIONAL { ?article schema:about ?item; schema:isPartOf <https://en.wikipedia.org/>; schema:name ?wikipediaLabel}'
        'SERVICE wikibase:label {'
        f'bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "{lang}" .'
        '}'
        '}'
        'GROUP BY ?article ?item ?itemLabel ?itemDescription ?main_category ?wikipediaLabel'
    )

    # URL for the Wikidata Query Service
    sparql_service_url = "https://query.wikidata.org/sparql"
    
    # Execute the query using a helper function (assumed to be defined elsewhere)
    result_table = query_wikidata(sparql_query, sparql_service_url)
    
    return result_table
In [6]:
def search_wikidata_altlabel_en(label, lang='en'):
    sparql_query = (
        'SELECT DISTINCT ?article ?item ?itemLabel ?itemDescription (GROUP_CONCAT(DISTINCT(?entity_type); separator = ", ") AS ?entity_type_list) ?main_category ?wikipediaLabel (GROUP_CONCAT(DISTINCT(?altLabel); separator = ", ") AS ?altLabel_list) WHERE {'
        f'?item ?altLabel "{label}"@en.'

        'MINUS { ?item wdt:P31 wd:Q4167410}'

        'OPTIONAL { ?article schema:about ?item;'
        'schema:isPartOf <https://en.wikipedia.org/>;'
        'schema:name ?wikipediaLabel}'
        'OPTIONAL { ?item skos:altLabel ?altLabel .}'
        'SERVICE wikibase:label {'
        f'bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "{lang}" .'
        '}}'
        'GROUP BY ?article ?item ?itemLabel ?itemDescription ?main_category ?wikipediaLabel'
    )
    # to query another endpoint, change the URL for the service and the query
    sparql_service_url = "https://query.wikidata.org/sparql"
    result_table = query_wikidata(sparql_query, sparql_service_url)
    return result_table

1.1.4 Save The Dataframe into a Excel File¶

In [8]:
def rename_columns(data_df):
    """
    Renames columns in a DataFrame by removing the ".value" suffix.

    This function renames columns in a DataFrame by removing the ".value" suffix from each column name.
    
    Args:
        data_df (pandas.DataFrame): The DataFrame whose columns are to be renamed.

    Returns:
        pandas.DataFrame: A DataFrame with columns renamed by removing the ".value" suffix.
    """
    # Renaming columns by removing the ".value" suffix
    data_df = data_df.rename(columns=lambda col: col.replace(".value", ""))

    return data_df
In [9]:
def save_df_to_excel(df):
    """
    Saves a DataFrame to an Excel file after renaming its columns.

    This function renames columns in the input DataFrame by removing the ".value" suffix, then saves the DataFrame
    to an Excel file named 'wikidata_data_en.xlsx'.

    Args:
        df (pandas.DataFrame): The DataFrame to be saved to the Excel file.

    Returns:
        None
    """
    # Renaming columns
    df = rename_columns(df)
    
    # Checking if the DataFrame has rows
    if df.shape[0]:
        # Saving DataFrame to Excel file
        df.to_excel('wikidata_data_en.xlsx', index=False, header=True)

This function reads the mentioned Excel sheets

# Set random seed for reproducibility
random_seed = 42
In [11]:
def accumulate_data(df, clmn):
    """
    Accumulates data from a DataFrame by querying a SPARQL endpoint to fetch information about named entities.

    This function takes a DataFrame containing named entities in a specific column and iterates over each entity
    to query a SPARQL endpoint (knowledge graph) to fetch additional information about the entities. It accumulates
    the fetched data into a large DataFrame and returns it.

    Args:
        df (pandas.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing named entities.
        clmn (str): The name of the column in the DataFrame containing the named entities.

    Returns:
        pandas.DataFrame: A DataFrame containing accumulated data fetched from the SPARQL endpoint.
    """
    # Define columns for the large DataFrame
    DF_COLUMNS = ['item.type', 'item.value', 'itemLabel.xml:lang', 'itemLabel.type', 'itemLabel.value',
                  'itemDescription.xml:lang', 'itemDescription.type', 'itemDescription.value', 'entity_type.type',
                  'entity_type.value', 'main_category.type', 'main_category.value', 'altLabel_list.type',
                  'altLabel_list.value']

    # Initialize an empty DataFrame with the defined columns
    large_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=DF_COLUMNS)

    # Iterate over each named entity in the specified column
    for name in df[clmn]:
        # Query the SPARQL endpoint to fetch information about the named entity
        data_result = search_wikidata_label_en(name)
        print('From Label:', name, "---", data_result.shape[0])

        # Check if the search result contains data
        if data_result.shape[0] > 0:
            # Concatenate the fetched data with the large DataFrame
            large_df = pd.concat([large_df, data_result], ignore_index=True)
        # If the search result is empty, try searching using alternate labels
        elif data_result.shape[0] == 0:
            data_result = search_wikidata_altlabel_en(name)
            print('From Alternate Label:', name, "---", data_result.shape[0])

            # Check if the alternate label search result contains data
            if data_result.shape[0] > 0:
                # Concatenate the fetched data with the large DataFrame
                large_df = pd.concat([large_df, data_result], ignore_index=True)

    # Return the accumulated DataFrame
    return large_df

# difne a dataframe to hold the data from all sheets
df_all= pd.DataFrame()
# Iterate through the AWRAQ CSV file to read the data from the spesified sheets, coulmns names from the SHEETS_INFO disctionary
for sheet, COLUMNS  in tqdm(SHEETS_INFO.items()):
  print('sheet', sheet ,'COLUMNS', COLUMNS)
  df=pd.read_excel('awraq.xlsx',sheet)
  df.dropna()
  df = df.sample(n=300, random_state=random_seed)
  df.sort_values(COLUMNS[0])
  df.drop_duplicates(keep='first', inplace=True)
# define a new dataframe for the arabic labels for each sheet
  df_names =df[COLUMNS]
  print(COLUMNS[0])
# call search_wikidata method to get data and accumalate the data for each sheet in the big Dataframe
  df_all=accumulate_data(df_names,COLUMNS[0])

def get_QIdentifier(url):
    if url is not None:
        res = url.split('/')
        return res[-1]
    return None

# Configure logging
logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)
logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

# Initialize the Wikipedia API with a custom user agent
wiki_wiki = wikipediaapi.Wikipedia(
    user_agent="YourUserAgent/1.0",
    language='en'
)

# Function to get first two sentences from Wikipedia summary
def get_first_two_sentences(summary):
    sentences = summary.split('. ')[:2]  # Split summary into sentences and select the first two
    return '. '.join(sentences) + '.'  # Join the selected sentences and add a period at the end

# Function to get summary from Wikipedia
def get_wikipedia_summary(title):
    try:
        page = wiki_wiki.page(title)
        if page.exists():
            summary = page.summary
            return get_first_two_sentences(summary)
        else:
            logger.warning(f"Page does not exist for title: {title}")
            return None
    except Exception as e:
        logger.error(f"Error fetching summary for title {title}: {e}")
        return None

# Assuming df is your DataFrame with the 'wikipediaLabel' attribute


# Fetch summaries directly from 'wikipediaLabel' attribute
unique_df['FirstTwoSentences'] = unique_df['wikipediaLabel'].apply(lambda title: get_wikipedia_summary(title))

# Verify the resulting DataFrame
print(df.head())
print(df.info())

def calculate_string_length(column):
    return column.str.len()
In [7]:
# Define the word count function
def word_count(column):
    if isinstance(column, str):  # Check if the column value is a string
        review_list = column.split()
        return len(review_list)
    else:
        return 0  # Return 0 if the value is not a string

def visualize(col1, col2):
    print(f'Visualizing {col1} and {col2}')
    
    # Ensure infinite values are converted to NaNs
    df[col1] = df[col1].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)
    df[col2] = df[col2].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.boxplot(data=df[[col1, col2]])
    plt.ylabel('Values')
    plt.title('Box Plot')
    

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Research Question 1: How does the length of descriptions and the word count differ between data obtained from Wikipedia and Wikidata, and what are the differences in the average word length and mean sentence length between the two sources?¶

To address this question, we analyzed the word counts and sentence lengths of descriptions from Wikipedia and Wikidata.

Key Observations:¶

  1. Word Counts: From the first boxplot chart comparing the word counts of Wikidata and Wikipedia descriptions, it's evident that:

    • The median word count for Wikipedia is significantly higher than that for Wikidata.
    • Wikipedia descriptions are generally longer and more detailed, while Wikidata descriptions tend to be more concise.
    • Both datasets exhibit outliers in terms of word count, suggesting variations in description lengths within each source.

  2. Word length: From the second boxplot chart comparing the word length of Wikidata and Wikipedia descriptions, it's evident that:

    • The median word length for Wikipdata is significantly higher than that for Wikipedia.
    • Both datasets exhibit outliers in terms of word length, suggesting variations in description lengths within each source.

  3. Sentence Lengths: To further investigate, we calculated the mean sentence length for descriptions from both sources. From the boxplot of Wikidata descriptions, we observe that:

    • While Wikidata descriptions are shorter in terms of word count, they may contain longer sentences on average.
    • The higher median and range in sentence length for Wikidata descriptions compared to Wikipedia suggest a tendency for longer sentences despite shorter overall descriptions.

Summary:¶

In summary, there is a noticeable difference between Wikipedia and Wikidata in terms of description lengths and sentence structures:

  • Word Count: Wikipedia descriptions are generally longer and more detailed compared to those on Wikidata.
  • Wod Length: Wikidata words' lengths are generally longer than Wikipedia.
  • Sentence Length: Despite being more concise, Wikidata descriptions tend to have longer sentences on average compared to Wikipedia.

These differences underscore the distinct purposes and styles of the two platforms, with Wikipedia focusing on comprehensive coverage and detailed descriptions, while Wikidata emphasizes succinct, structured data. uctured data.ctured data.uctured data.

In [32]:
def visualize(col1, col2):
    print(f'Visualizing {col1} and {col2}')
    
    # Ensure infinite values are converted to NaNs
    df[col1] = df[col1].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)
    df[col2] = df[col2].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
    
    # Histogram for col1
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.histplot(df[col1].dropna(), kde=True, bins=30, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(df[col1].mean(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean: {df[col1].mean():.2f}')
    plt.axvline(df[col1].median(), color='yellow', linestyle='-', label=f'Median: {df[col1].median():.2f}')
    plt.xlabel(col1)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title(f'Histogram of {col1}')
    plt.legend()
    
    # Histogram for col2
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.histplot(df[col2].dropna(), kde=True, bins=30, color='green')
    plt.axvline(df[col2].mean(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Mean: {df[col2].mean():.2f}')
    plt.axvline(df[col2].median(), color='yellow', linestyle='-', label=f'Median: {df[col2].median():.2f}')
    plt.xlabel(col2)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title(f'Histogram of {col2}')
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Research Question 2: How do the distributions of the lengths of descriptions, word counts, word lengths, and average sentence lengths differ between data obtained from Wikipedia and Wikidata?¶

To address this research question, we analyzed the distributions of description lengths, word counts, word lengths, and average sentence lengths for data obtained from Wikipedia and Wikidata.

Key Observations from the Histograms:¶

  1. Description Lengths and Word Counts: The first set of histogram charts compares the word counts of descriptions from Wikipedia and Wikidata. Both distributions are right-skewed.

    • Wikipedia:
      • Mean Word Count: 44.81 words
      • Median Word Count: 40 words
      • This indicates that Wikipedia descriptions are relatively long, with a significant number of descriptions extending beyond the median length.
    • Wikidata:
      • Mean Word length: 5 words
      • Median Word length: 4 words
      • Wikidata descriptions are much shorter, reflecting the platform's focus on succinct, structured data.

    The stark contrast in the word counts between Wikipedia and Wikidata highlights the difference in their content structure and purpose. Wikipedia aims to provide comprehensive, detailed information, whereas Wikidata prioritizes brevity and concise data representation.

  2. Word Length: The second set of histogram charts compares the word lengths of descriptions from Wikipedia and Wikidata.

    • Wikipedia:
      • Distribution Shape: Bell-shaped
      • Mean Word Length: 5.31 characters
      • Median Word Length: 5.26 characters
      • The bell-shaped distribution suggests that most words in Wikipedia descriptions are of moderate length, reflecting a balance between common and specialized vocabulary.
    • Wikidata:
      • Distribution Shape: Bimodal
      • Mean Word Length: 6.18 characters
      • Median Word Length: 6 characters
      • The bimodal distribution indicates two prevalent word length categories in Wikidata descriptions. This suggests a mixture of very short and relatively longer words, potentially due to the structured nature of the data which might include both brief terms and specific technical jargon.

    The analysis shows that, on average, words in Wikidata descriptions are slightly longer than those in Wikipedia. This difference might be attributed to the nature of the content, where Wikidata often uses more specific terms, while Wikipedia includes a broader range of vocabulary.

  3. Average Sentence Lengths: The final set of histogram charts compares the average sentence lengths of descriptions from Wikipedia and Wikidata.

    • Wikipedia:
      • Mean Sentence Length: 131.03 characters
      • Median Sentence Length: 122.03 characters
      • This shows that Wikipedia sentences tend to be significantly longer, consistent with the detailed and explanatory nature of the content.
    • Wikidata:
      • Mean Sentence Length: 54.72 characters
      • Median Sentence Length: 31 characters
      • Wikidata sentences are much shorter, emphasizing brevity and precision.

    The significant difference in sentence lengths between the two sources underscores the varying content styles. Wikipedia's longer sentences are suited for comprehensive coverage of topics, while Wikidata's shorter sentences are optimized for concise, data-focused entries.

Conclusion:¶

The histograms reveal significant differences between Wikipedia and Wikidata in terms of description lengths, word counts, word lengths, and average sentence lengths. Wikipedia's content is characterized by longer, more detailed descriptions with higher word counts and longer sentences, making it ideal for in-depth information. In contrast, Wikidata descriptions are much shorter, with lower word counts and shorter sentences, reflecting its purpose of providing quick, concise data. Additionally, while Wikipedia's word length distribution is bell-shaped, indicating a balanced vocabulary, Wikidata's bimodal distribution highlights the presence of both very short and relatively longer words.

These insights underscore the distinct roles that Wikipedia and Wikidata play in the information ecosystem, catering to different user needs and preferences.

from wordcloud import WordCloud
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Combine 'FirstTwoSentences' from all rows into a single text
text = ' '.join(df['FirstTwoSentences'])

# Create the WordCloud object
wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=400, background_color='white').generate(text)

# Display the WordCloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.title('Word Cloud of Wikipedia description')
plt.axis('off')  # Hide axis
plt.show()
